{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to luca-palmieri's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "marty-cagan",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@luca-palmieri",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Mini-retro: design discussion worked well, context loss caused repeated approvals",
    "content": "Mini-retro observations from product:\n\n**What went well:**\n- Pre-implementation design discussion worked exactly as intended. Luca's design proposal gave every reviewer a chance to shape the approach before code was written. Scott's renames (WaitingOn, Resolved) and the project_id deferral decision were much cheaper to make at design time than after implementation.\n- Scope discipline was strong. We built exactly what US-GTD-5 calls for — no gold plating, no missing pieces (with convert-to-next-action correctly deferred as a follow-up commit within Step 8).\n- The \"Received\" label and the Resolved domain language landed well. Good collaboration between domain modeling and UX.\n\n**What could improve:**\n- Context loss caused repeated approval requests. I gave three separate approvals for the same commit. This is wasteful for reviewers. If there's a way to make consensus tallies more durable across context compactions, that would help.\n- The staging gap (fixes on disk but not staged) created unnecessary confusion about whether blocking items were actually addressed. A quick `git diff --cached` check before requesting re-review would catch this.\n\n**No process changes to propose.** The pipeline worked correctly — the a11y review caught real issues, they were fixed before commit, and CI is green. This is the system working as designed."
  }
}
